title: A Long-Term Follow-Up Study of Oral ELND005 (AZD-103) in Subjects With Alzheimer's Disease
description_brief: The purpose of this study is to evaluate the long-term safety and tolerability of ELND005 beyond the 18 months of treatment in original randomized and blinded clinical trail ELND005-AD201.

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails: All participants who enrolled in long term follow up prior to 15 Dec 2009 received ELND005 2000 mg BID; due to protocol amendment, all participants who enrolled in long term follow up after 15 Dec 2009 received ELND005 250 mg BID

groups.title: Placebo/ELND005 2000mg BID
groups.description: In the original randomized and blinded clinical trial (ELND005-AD201 NCT00568776) participants were randomized to receive Placebo for 78 weeks. Participants enrolled in ELND005-AD251 long term follow-up prior to 15 Dec 2009 were assigned to receive ELND005 2000 mg PO BID for 48 weeks.

outcomeMeasures.title: Treatment Emergent Adverse Events (TEAEs)
outcomeMeasures.description: Safety and Tolerability was assessed by the incidence of Treatment Emergent Adverse Events (TEAEs)
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: As a result of safety findings, effective 15 December 2009, all 50 patients at the 2000 mg BID dose were withdrawn from the study. Subsequently patients who were on placebo or 250 mg BID in Study AD201 received 250 mg BID in Study AD251. Only Arms who completed the study per the protocol were included in the analysis.

adverseEventsModule.timeFrame: Adverse events were recorded for each patient, starting from the time the consent form was signed until completion of the study (Week 54, Follow-up).
adverseEventsModule.description: For all adverse event (AE) summaries, if a patient had more than one AE within a preferred term the patient was counted once, at the maximum severity and with the closest relationship to study drug. If a patient had more than one AE within a system organ class (SOC), the patient was similarly counted once when reporting results for that SOC.

explanation_target: Reason: The investigational product ELND005 is scyllo-inositol, an orally administered endogenous inositol stereoisomer developed to inhibit/anti-aggregate amyloid-β (i.e., target Alzheimer’s pathology) — this indicates a disease-targeting mechanism rather than a pure symptomatic (cognitive-enhancer or neuropsychiatric) effect. citeturn0search1turn0search0

Act: Extracted details — drug name ELND005 (formerly AZD-103), route oral, mechanism described as an "amyloid anti-aggregation agent" and tested in Phase 2 (ELND005-AD201) for mild–moderate AD; pharmacokinetic work shows CSF and brain penetration consistent with a small-molecule-type profile. Based on these attributes, the correct category is "disease-targeted small molecule." citeturn0search5turn0search6

Reflect: The classification was checked against the category definitions: ELND005 is not a biologic (it is a small endogenous stereoisomer taken orally), it is intended to modify amyloid pathology (disease-targeted), and clinical reports describe biomarker effects on Aβ but no robust clinical efficacy in the phase 2 trial — this supports placing it as a disease-targeted small molecule rather than a cognitive enhancer or symptom-directed agent. citeturn0search0turn0search1

Web-search findings / supporting sources: (1) Neurology / PubMed report of the Phase 2 randomized trial describes ELND005 as an oral "amyloid anti-aggregation agent" (scyllo-inositol), reports safety and biomarker (CSF Aβ) findings but no significant clinical efficacy at primary endpoints. citeturn0search1turn0search0 (2) ClinicalTrials.gov / trial record maps ELND005 to AZD-103 and describes the drug as scyllo-inositol investigating inhibition/prevention of amyloid buildup in AD. citeturn0search5 (3) Pharmacokinetic studies show ELND005 is measurable in CSF and brain after oral dosing, consistent with a small-molecule oral agent crossing into CNS. citeturn0search6turn0search7
